metadata.name: Hexagones Landscape #338
metadata.description:
An undulating (sometimes) landscape made up of hexagons (or "Hexagones" laying in wait) to celebrate the first birthday of fxhash. Written at the last minute the weekend before the birthday week.

A simpler 16 colour version of this project was originally coded on an Atari ST 512, about 32 years ago, figured it was time to update it.

INSTRUCTIONS ::

h - Toggle high-res
s - Download and save image

PRINTING INSTRUCTIONS ::

High-res will output a 6,553 x 8,192 image, at 300dpi it should print at...

21.84 x 27.3 inches
55.47 x 69.3 cm

metadata.name: Snake Alley #175
metadata.description:
Snake Alley is a place in my neighborhood where the sidewalk is narrowly bounded by low-hanging branches on one side and a steep ditch one the other. I have seen countless snakes dart across the sidewalk there at dusk. 

I always wind up at Snake Alley, wearing sandals, at dusk.

This generative system creates unique outputs for each hash. The compositions are organized like spokes through a series of concentric rings, like the Dharmachakra, however these are twisted and centered around an out-spiraling function. Higher-torque versions look more twisted and gnarled, while low-torque versions look like rays emanating from the center.

A number of branches connect each outer ring with its adjacent, inner ring. The layers of branches fill the space with low, medium, or high density - full of circles drawn from the outer layers to the innermost layer. The circles themselves are small or large, within each output.

Fifteen color palettes named after different kinds of snakes were used to lightly color the edges, each drawn with equal likelihood. The titles and colors were adapted from different snake species, typically variants found in the southeastern US, when different colorations occur in other regions. The coral, corn, and milk snakes around Charleston have similar coloration in nature, and their similar color gradients reflect this fact.

I originally composed this artwork in the R Statistics language. I translated the system to p5.js for the one-year anniversary of fxhash. Proceeds from sales will go to Processing.org, the organization that is developing p5.js. #fxhashturnsone 

Verified NFT collectors can purchase a fine art print for their unique token at vadenart.com

About the artist: Kenny Vaden is a generative artist based in Charleston, SC. His art experience included drawing, painting, stained glass apprenticeships, and nature photography. Vadenâ€™s code-based artworks are available online as limited edition or single edition fine art prints, as well as NFTs on Quantum.art, Flamingo DAO Flutter, OpenSea, Objkt, fxhash, and Foundation. More information about the artist and artwork is available on vadenart.com

metadata.name: Monsoon #257
metadata.description:
Optimization. It's something that haunts all programmers. Including me. But no longer! Monsoon is a study into the optimization of particle systems for the web. Looking especially deep into dynamic grids and dynamic frame rates.

As for the piece itself, it's a reference to how busy this modern world is. How we're all constantly on the go, whether that is physically, or mentally. Almost feeling like a monsoon. A storm of information. A storm of life. A storm of work. A storm of thoughts. A storm of emotions. A storm of everything. And it's all so fast.

As are the particles. They're all moving around these cyclones of information. Glowing up like neon signs in a busy city. Moving so fast it's almost a blur. Forming into something greater than the sum of its parts.

metadata.name: Modulation #190
metadata.description:
Isometric cityscapes, patterns and geometries generated by trigonometric functions and rendered as SVG.

The SVG can be saved by pressing "s" on the full-screen view.
A PNG version can be exported by pressing "e" on the full-screen view.

By default the dimensions of the export are 6000Ã—7500.
These dimensions can be changed by adding, for example, ?w=12000 to the full-screen page URL, where w is the desired width. Then press "e" to export at this size.

metadata.description:

metadata.name: Annum #1251
metadata.description:
This project is being released in celebration of the 1 year aniversary of Achromat, my first release on fxhash. In addition to being inspired by Achromat, aspects of other previous projects have been incorporated. My deepest gratitude to all who have collected my work over the past year.

In live mode, add &size=<YOUR_PIXEL_SIZE> to change the pixel size of the image for export (Right click to save). For example, &size=4000 will set the width of the image to be 4000 pixels.

50% of primary sales go to Savepakistan.

metadata.name: Lineage #180
metadata.description:
Lineage is a collaboration between Tim Maxwell and Twistie that attempts to bridge the gap between traditional and generative art.
256 outputs are generated using 100% JavaScript + p5js, written by Twistie, in the distinctive style of Tim Maxwell. The code tries to replicate not only the style, but also the process and inaccuracies that go into a drawing.

Each iteration has a unique title. 
All 256 rendered outputs and their respective titles will be displayed in high quality on https://twistie.org/lineage. 

10 lucky owners will have their iteration hand drawn and signed. They will each receive the physical 1/1 as well as an NFT version.

Press 's' on keyboard to save in high-res. This is how the art is intended to be viewed.

Hardware acceleration on Chromium-based browsers can impact performance!

metadata.name: Tork #61
metadata.description:
Tork is a generative artwork that invites you into a frenzied, distorted space where order collapses in on itself and clarity slips away.

What started as an exploration into recursive grid subdivision quickly evolved as our good friend Entropy invited itself in and I couldn't resist the temptation to let it take control.

Created to celebrate the 'fxhash turns one' anniversary mint event. #fxhashturnsone

----------

Interaction:

* Press 's' in the Live Mode to save as PNG
* Watch the drawing unfold by adding '&build=1' to the URL in Live Mode
* Change the size by adding '&size=1' to the URL in Live Mode [1=1000, 2=2000, 3=4000, 4=8000]

Features:

* A broad set of colour palettes, subtle and not-so-subtle variations in paint modes, and dramatic layer distortions to discover.
